objkt.name: Julia's Magical Bulbs - The Second Power #22

metadata.name: Julia's Magical Bulbs - The Second Power #22
metadata.description:
Julia's Magical Bulbs are 3D dimensional fractals, based on the Julia Sets of the Mandelbulb fractal.

The token is interactive, use your mouse-wheel to zoom-in and see all the little details. You will find a menu in the lower-right corner which allows you to play with the iterations and camera position. You can also render high-resolution images here.

A little bit of magic happens when you select low iteration values, perhaps your token will even default to this. 

Technical:

Not all browsers support multi-threaded modules, the fallback mode is quite slow. Try Chrome if your browser is not supported.

Calculated in full 64-bit on the CPU (not the GPU) for more accurate and detailed images.

metadata.name: Light reverberations #39
metadata.description:
“The tinnitus like silence tearing the eardrums; a glare of darkness burned into the retina. “


As a visual & sound designer, my routine job is more related to new media installations, interactive programming design and lighting design. Explore to different luminaries and light sources, I gradually discover the relationship between light and sound waves. The role of reverberations are often sculptured the space when processing sounds, just like the lights play a similar role in 3D worlds. Reflections in the space make the sound more realistic, while the presence of light emphasis the dimensionality and depth of the space as well.

These scenes made of light and time remind me the painting and sculptures in the early 20th century, Futurism, which is characterized by technology, speed and violence. Umberto Boccioni and Gino Severini for instance. Nowadays, when we are free to deal with digital art beyond the existence of print or various archival forms, will it be an art movement called meta-futurism? Perhaps only things beyond our imagination can be called the future.

The project has been described during testing as being like picking up a camera that has fallen into space. It could be a collection of extreme brightness or endless darkness. If you decide to go into the space,  a carefully risk assessment is necessary.


Controls:

Click -> activate rotate control. (swipe gesture on mobile device)

Esc -> exit rotate and restart the rendering. (one tap on mobile device)

(Explore your own world by clicking on the canvas and rotate the viewpoint, tap “esc” to see the new result.)

The code used to calculate path tracing environment is from the three.js-PathTracing-Renderer ([https://github.com/erichlof/THREE.js-PathTracing-Renderer](https://github.com/erichlof/THREE.js-PathTracing-Renderer)), created by Erich Loftis.

metadata.name: random(four) #141
metadata.description:
Building on four’s participation in the Blind Gallery Bear Market Edition, random(four) replaces the use of tezos price data with randomized inputs.  Other qualities/design aspects have been revised slightly to allow for a more diverse set of outputs. 

Made with p5js, triangles, and no tezos price data.

Press 1-9 to render higher quality outputs; rendering time will vary.

metadata.name: Nothing Remains #25
metadata.description:
The only time I ever received corporal punishment – something that was still legal in schools during the 1970s – was in Double Maths with Mrs Robinson. The log book spread out before me seemed less appealing than talking with my friends at the back of the classroom, and so it was I found myself, palm outstretched, feeling the whack of Mrs. Robinson's ruler, ten times over. "Math sucks." Or so I thought.

Back then I knew nothing of the beauty that I would later see in Mathematics – something which became apparent as I taught myself to code, especially using Processing.

This work – based on code I've been playing around with since 2009 – is my small homage to that beauty. Originally based on Ulam spirals, I've then played around with that starting formula to create an infinite numbers of patterns using square roots, cosines and modulus. If only they had shown me these possibilities when I was younger I may have avoided the dreaded ruler of Mrs. Robinson.

metadata.name: Updraft #23
metadata.description:
UPDRAFT seeks to reproduce the beauty of tornadoes and other vortices in a minimalist style and simple shapes, thus highlighting the purity of the lines of these fascinating objects.

If the tornado of life scares you, remember that while you will probably be a little shaken and confused on your journey, you will end up at the top of it. That's the beauty of the updraft.

[S] or [Double-Tap] when viewing in full screen to save a 4000x4000 PNG image

Artist: Estienne
August 2022
Made with p5.js
Best viewed on Chrome or Chromium-based browsers

metadata.name: Sketch E #149
metadata.description:
Sketch is an open-ended series. Works evolve as I code a generative project, sometimes drastically. Intermediate works usually don't see the light of day - they get archived and forgotten. This series is snapshots of different forms along the way - each standing alone, but also part of a larger meandering work flow. The word Sketch implies incompleteness. This project may end up being two works, or it could evolve for years. Part of the joy of generative art is never knowing what's around the corner. I have no set schedule. There may be multiple Sketches released a week, or it could be weeks or months between drops. I have no idea where Sketch is heading and there is no guarantee of cohesiveness from Sketch to Sketch. Color palettes and forms will change as new ideas are explored.

Sketch E. Rebuilding after the disruption of Sketch D. Color palettes from A-D remain and more palettes are introduced based on Werner's Nomenclature of Colors, first published in 1814, which served as a classification guide for natural colors before photography became commonplace and used by Charles Darwin during voyages on the HMS Beagle. Grid size, padding, and colors vary.

Press the spacebar to see the framework and press the left/right arrow keys to construct and deconstruct.

metadata.name: Lucky Oracles #771
metadata.description:
"Lucky Oracles" is part of the fxhash interactive minting experience at Art Basel, Basel 2022

Eko33, is a Swiss-French generative artist who has been at the forefront of digital arts since 1999 when he started writing code to create generative artworks and installations. He made his debut using a Commodore SX-64 and floppy disks. Since then, his work has been exhibited in Museums, International art fairs, and biennales. His work is focused on nonfigurative, generative art while using custom algorithms and innovative technology.

Official Website: https://www.eko33.com/ Official Twitter account: https://twitter.com/eko3316 Official Instagram account: https://www.instagram.com/eko33studio/ https://linktr.ee/eko33 "I create deterministic generative art based on crypto hash seeds. Maximizing algorithmic diversity."

If you want to receive an e-mail alert when I release new artwork subscribe here => https://eko33.com/email-alerts
